Text1: I think having direct conversations with a wide variety of young kids from a variety of different backgrounds gave me a well-rounded view of how the current education system is built. All these kids were smart, funny, talkative, and intuitive yet would remark on wildly different experiences depending on what or where they were schooled. All these conversations exposed me to the fact that the reasons behind educational deficits or surpluses across the city aren't just a race or class or familial or location issue, it's a mixture of all these factors and more. Diversity as a concept shouldn't be a benchmark, it should be a standard.
Text2: My community partner required me to create connections with a wide variety of kids of many ages to make them feel comfortable and talkative within the space. However, I found that instead, I should focus on forging friendships and comradery between me and the kids I was working with. When doing so, I found that first I was able to be a part of some fantastic conversations about who these kids were and why they liked what they liked. Second, I found that once they opened up, the kids' ideas were much more creative and expressive and they went to me much more for homework help. The organization's main goals can only be achieved if the kids feel the space is safe and their ideas will be heard, and I think I contributed to progressing the space even more so to those levels.

Text1: Engaging with the Museum of Social Justice and developing a learning module on social inequality issues in Los Angeles, particularly focusing on water resources, has profoundly impacted my understanding of diversity and its intersection with social justice. Through extensive research and interaction with the museum's exhibitions and resources, I encountered a diverse array of perspectives and experiences related to social inequality. Exploring the different dimensions of inequality also provided insights into how social inequality intertwines with other forms of oppression, such as race, ethnicity, socioeconomic status, and environmental justice. Additionally, engaging with the museum's community-driven approach and attending exhibitions like "Comfort Women" evoked empathy towards marginalized communities and their struggles for justice and equality, empowering me to become a more effective advocate for social change and diversity within my own community.  Overall, this community engagement experience has broadened my understanding of diversity and equipped me with valuable insights and tools to contribute to advocacy efforts for social change and diversity in my community.
Text2: During this quarter, I actively collaborated with the Museum of Social Justice to develop a comprehensive learning module addressing social inequality issues in Los Angeles, focusing on water resources. Through thorough research and content creation, I contributed to enhancing the museum's educational resources, empowering community members across age groups to understand and engage with pressing social justice issues. Additionally, I participated in the museum's community-driven initiatives, such as attending the opening day of their newest exhibition, "Comfort Women," and engaging with local voices and stories, amplifying marginalized narratives and fostering empathy within the community. Overall, my contributions this quarter have aimed at enriching educational resources, amplifying marginalized voices, fostering empathy, and promoting awareness and advocacy for social change within the community served by the Museum of Social Justice.

Text1: The Cancer Care Institute treats a very diverse range of patients which couldn’t be done without their diverse team. The staff at Cancer Care Institute is very ethnically and curlturally diverse, with hispanic, latino, black, and middle eastern directors, administrators, nurses, etc. running the show. None of this amazing work could be done as successfully without the deep rooted passion of this diverse team. Every single person on the team brings a diverse set of skills and is able to speak their language to each patient, which in this office is predominantly Spanish or Armenian. Having a diverse staff definitely makes the institutions very empathetic towards people from al walks of life, as they handle each patient as their own family. Each staff member contributes to the institution in their unique way by connecting with each patient on a more personal level.
Text2: The institute and its volunteers utilize a multitude of non-profit organizations which include over 20 non-profit funds associated with pharmaceutical companies as well as over 50 non-profit organizations that dedicate resources to over 30 different types of cancers. Every patient who is unable to afford their medical care is screened, financially, and if they meet appropriate criteria, they will be matched to as many nonprofit funds to assist them with their financial needs to pay for their cancer care.

Text1: Working with children who have Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) was an incredibly rewarding experience that I truly cherished. The opportunity to interact with these amazing kids opened my eyes to the unique ways they see and understand the world, making each day a learning experience filled with moments of joy and discovery. Additionally, this journey introduced me to some of the most friendly and selfless individuals I've ever had the privilege to meet. Their dedication to making a difference in the lives of these children was inspiring, and their kindness and generosity of spirit have left a lasting impact on me. This experience has not only enriched my understanding and appreciation for the challenges faced by those with ASD but also highlighted the profound difference compassionate and dedicated support can make in their lives.
Text2: Throughout this quarter, my role involved directly supporting children in focusing and actively participating in their sessions. I also helped support occupational therapists (OTs) and recreational therapists (RTs) in their therapeutic activities. My involvement ranged from setting up creative play scenarios that aligned with therapeutic goals of the kids to facilitating group activities that encouraged social interaction and cooperation among the children. Text1: Through working with BookSustain, I interacted with various communities and organizations, such as shelters and community centers, that serve very diverse populations. This exposure gave me insight to the different socioeconomics backgrounds and challenges faced by individuals in the greater Los Angeles area. BookSustain also made me aware of the educational disparities that exist within my community. I learned about the unequal access to education resources and how this directly affects literacy levels among different demographic groups.
Text2: From working with BookSustain, I got to collaborate with them to develop a plan to expand their social impact. Prior to our involvement, BookSustain primarily collected and distributed books to various locations. While this was beneficial, it lacked a clear measure of whether these efforts were effectively achieving their larger goal of expanding literacy. My group and I facilitated connections between BookSustain and charter schools, as well as other volunteer organizations sharing a similar mission to promote literacy. By doing so, we ensured that the donated books were actively used through reading activities, thus contributing to our shared goal. Additionally, we addressed BookSustain's funding challenges by conducting research and presenting them with various methods and strategies to generate revenue. These included innovative approaches such as auctioning off signed books by renowned authors, seeking grants and donations, and exploring avenues like selling books on third-party platforms like Amazon.These are a few of the strategies we presented to BookSustain, and they are likely to have a lasting impact on their operations and the community they serve, promoting access to knowledge and increasing the literacy rate in the Los Angeles area.
